The Telegraph - Calcutta : Business

 Corporate Briefs

 Ballarpur Industries has closed its international offering of zero coupon foreign currency convertible bonds (FCCBs) aggregating to $60 million. The company has informed the BSE that the FCCBs, due for redemption on July 13, 2010, would be convertible at an initial price of Rs 180 per share. The proceeds of the issue will be used for capital expenditure and repayment of existing FCCbs. 

 Samsung India has launched eight models of top-loading and six of front-loading automatic washing machines with silver nano technology. The top-loading washing machines are in the capacity range of 6 kg to 9 kg and are priced between Rs 12,990 and Rs 25,990. The front-loading machines have a capacity range of 5.8 kg to 9 kg, priced between Rs 22,900 and Rs 75,900.

 HSBC Holdings plc has tied up with SAS to put a cap on payment card fraud. SAS solution will be implemented in HSBC?s debit and credit card businesses. HSBC has a portfolio of over 100 million cards. 

 Dr Fixit Institute has signed a pact with the US-based National Roofing Contractors Association. The agreement will give Dr Fixit Institute access to NRCA?a training modules for the installation of roofing and waterproofing materials, specially customised to suit Indian conditions.

 JK Paper has commissioned an offline blade coating plant at its existing facility in Orissa. The new plant will have a capacity of 46,000 tonnes per annum and will manufacture high-value coated paper. 

 Reliance Infocomm has introduced a colour handset priced at Rs 2,799. The company has also announced a bonus talktime of Rs 1,000 on purchase of any new handset from it. The bonus talktime offer is valid for new handsets activated between July 10 and July 31.

 Gujarat Tea Processors amp; Packers, which manage the WaghBakri Tea Group, has been awarded ISO 9001:2000 amp; HACCP (Hazard Analysis Critical Control Points) quality certificate. KPMG has assessed the company?s quality system. 

 Industrial Investment Bank of India has reported an operating profit of Rs 71 crore for 2004-05 against an operating loss of Rs 81 crore in 2003-04. The bank has recovered Rs 147 crore from its non-performing assets during the reporting fiscal compared with Rs 131 crore in the previous year.

 LG Electronics India has unveiled a 71-inch plasma television. It has also launched a 15-inch LCD television and a 42-inch plasma TV with a 10000:1 contrast ratio. The 71-inch plasma TV is priced at Rs 30 lakh.

